[16:04] <masak> I could give you a short tutorial, from an svn-er's perspective
[16:04] <masak> let's say you have just made a change. you go `git status`, and it lists your file as dirty
[16:05] <masak> you go `git add that-file`, and then `git status`, now it lists your file as added
[16:05] <masak> you go `git commit -m "I changed stuff"` and it commits it locally
[16:05] <masak> you go `git push` and it commits it to github
[16:05] <masak> those are the bare basics
[16:07] <masak> things to keep in mind: when you git-add stuff, you add not the file, but the changes made to that file since last commit/add
[16:07] <masak> also, git-revert does not Do What You (as an svn user) Think. instead, just checkout the file again
